0around%20just%20six%20percent%20of%20winners.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EBut%20things%20are%20getting%20better.%20Since%202000%2C%2031%20women%20have%20been%20awarded%20all%20prizes%20combined%2C%20almost%20three%20times%20as%20many%20as%20in%20the%20previous%20two%20decades.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EIn%202009%2C%20five%20women%20received%20a%20Nobel%20prize%2C%20including%20the%20first%20female%20laureate%20in%20economics%2C%20American%20Elinor%20Ostrom%20--%20a%20record%20yet%20to%20be%20equalled.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EEconomics%20has%20had%20the%20fewest%20women%20laureates%20at%202.2%20percent%2C%20lower%20than%20the%20science%20prizes%20combined%2C%20which%20have%20seen%203.7%20percent%20women%20laureates.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EWhile%20slightly%20more%20evenly%20distributed%2C%20literature%20is%20still%20largely%20a%20male%20affair%20with%2014.2%20percent%20women%20among%20laureates%2C%20with%20the%20peace%20prize%20faring%20slightly%20better%20at%2016%20percent.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20Nobel%20is%20an%20institution%20%26quot%3Bfor%20men%26quot%3B%2C%202022%20literature%20laureate%20Annie%20Ernaux%20of%20France%20told%20AFP.%20%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3ENevertheless%2C%20the%20first%20person%20to%20win%20the%20Nobel%20prize%20twice%20was%20Marie%20Curie%2C%20in%201903%20in%20physics%20and%20in%201911%20in%20chemistry.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Ch2%3E%3Cstrong%3ENo%20Nobel%20Prize%20in%20Mathematics%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%20%3Cp%3EThere%20has%20long%20been%20debate%20over%20why%20no%20prize%20was%20created%20for%20mathematics.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThere%20were%20longstanding%20rumours%20that%20it%20was%20in%20part%20because%20Alfred%20Nobel's%20lover%20had%20an%20affair%20with%20mathematician%20Gosta%20Mittag-Leffler%20--%20but%20in%20the%201980s%2C%20researchers%20were%20able%20to%20put%20that%20theory%20to%20rest.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3ESo%20why%20is%20there%20no%20prize%3F%20There%20are%20two%20likely%20explanations.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EIn%201895%2C%20when%20Nobel%20wro